nodes.body:
> I love the smell of deleted code in the evening. I'm amazed what gains new linters can yield :-)

Honestly, I was not expecting that so many `skip`s and various other unused tactics would be present...
!bench

Here are the [benchmark results](http://speed.lean-fro.org/mathlib4/run-detail/b511bb6b-8a61-4bc3-b7a8-e9bd30f1836c) for commit 7e216122bd8c1c85df62c2799f88f8ca7e7b0aff.
There were [significant changes](http://speed.lean-fro.org/mathlib4/compare/0b19543b-b3c2-4021-ad02-1e5f2abde81c/to/b511bb6b-8a61-4bc3-b7a8-e9bd30f1836c) against commit e8f233630b530da8986ef9d08d26f9eae01ac66e:
```diff
  Benchmark                              Metric         Change
  ============================================================
- ~Mathlib.Computability.TuringMachine   instructions    17.0%
```
Seems like some tactics weren't useless after all.

:facepalm: the file that slowed down is a file where I replaced some splits and assumptions into a single `aesop` call.  I reverted that change, since it was only flagged up by a `skip` and it should not be flagged by the second generation linter anyway!
!bench

Here are the [benchmark results](http://speed.lean-fro.org/mathlib4/run-detail/b565cfd6-7e50-47c7-8ae1-c3f2fc0a194f) for commit c8593e74c9dfb6adca561f723b35634b70dc4a54.
There were [no significant changes](http://speed.lean-fro.org/mathlib4/compare/0b19543b-b3c2-4021-ad02-1e5f2abde81c/to/b565cfd6-7e50-47c7-8ae1-c3f2fc0a194f) against commit e8f233630b530da8986ef9d08d26f9eae01ac66e.

Thanks!

Extra newline?
Yes, thanks!  Removed the extra line!
Doesn't `inferInstance` add extra junk that `by infer_instance` doesn't? Can you check the term is syntactically the same as it was before?

In its current form (with `inferInstance`):
```lean
#print evaluationPreservesLimits

def CategoryTheory.Limits.evaluationPreservesLimits.{v, u, v, u} : {C : Type u} 
  [inst : Category.{v, u} C] 
    {K : Type u} 
      [inst_1 : Category.{v, u} K]  [inst_2 : HasLimits C]  (k : K)  PreservesLimits ((evaluation K C).obj k) :=
fun {C} [Category.{v, u} C] {K} [Category.{v, u} K] [HasLimits C] k 
  { preservesLimitsOfShape := fun {x} _  inferInstance }
```
As it was before the change:
```lean
#print evaluationPreservesLimits

def CategoryTheory.Limits.evaluationPreservesLimits.{v, u, v, u} : {C : Type u} 
  [inst : Category.{v, u} C] 
    {K : Type u} 
      [inst_1 : Category.{v, u} K]  [inst_2 : HasLimits C]  (k : K)  PreservesLimits ((evaluation K C).obj k) :=
fun {C} [Category.{v, u} C] {K} [Category.{v, u} K] [HasLimits C] k 
  { preservesLimitsOfShape := fun {J}   inferInstance }
```
Seems that the only difference are the variable names.
Not sure that one is necessarily an improvement
I am happy to revert it back to where it was, but it is shorter and produces the same proof.  (Really identical, very long, output of `#print`.)
You will be able to golf further by doing `cases isEmpty_or_nonempty ` instead of that `by_cases
Ok, but I would definitely say that this is out of scope for this PR!

Seems like you haven't addressed the porting note, and removing `done` isn't a particularly great idea either.

I suggest you nolint `done` calls by default.
Isn't the issue that `rcases` does not realize that its pattern is over, since `|` could be an `or`?  Again, I can put the porting note back, but replacing `done` by `;` also "fixes" the error.

Here is an example:
```lean
example (x : Bool) (h : false  true) : True := by
  match x with
    | true => rcases h with 
    | false  -- <--- this is still part of `rcases`: I am calling `false` the `true` proof! x)
               exact .intro  -- <--- the proof if `h` is `false`
               exact .intro  -- <--- the proof if `h` is `true`
    | false => exact .intro   -- <--- the second `match` arm!

```
